{"title_page": "LGBT Culture in Tokyo", "text_new": "{{Merge to|LGBT culture in Tokyo|date=December 2019}}\n\nTokyo, Japan has the largest LGBT community all throughout Asia. Within the Japanese culture, it is very difficult for Japanese people to come out of the closet;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|date=2015|title=Same-Sex Marriage in Japan|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=12|issue=2|pages=160\u2013187|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2015.1016252}}</ref> the LGBT community faces homophobia amongst its own people.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Same-Sex Marriage in Japan|journal= Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=12|issue=2|pages=160\u2013187|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2015.1016252|year=2016}}</ref> In an online survey, there were only 5% of Japanese people that they knew someone who was Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, or Transgender which is reported to being second lowest out of the sixteen countries involved.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref>\n\nThere is a community in Japan called stone wall that aims to serve the LGBT community by providing them with an open and safe space that supports and celebrate their sexuality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+|last=|first=|date=|website=Stone Wall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This organization provides educational awareness, useful information, communicative online platforms, and fellowship opportunities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n===American Occupation of Japan (1945\u20131952)===\n\nBetween 1945\u20131952, the gay neighborhood of Ni-ch\u014dme<ref name=Baudinette>{{Cite journal|last=Baudinette|first=Thomas|date=2017|title=The spatialisation of desire in a Japanese gay district through signage|url=https://www.acme-journal.org/index.php/acme/article/view/1357|journal=ACME: An International Journal for Critical Geographies|volume=16|pages=501|via=}}</ref> came into existence which was around the time of the America Occupation of Japan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Luther & Boyd|first=Catherine & Douglas|date=1997|title=American Occupation Control Over Broadcasting in Japan|journal=Journal of Communication|volume=47|pages=39\u201359|doi=10.1111/j.1460-2466.1997.tb02705.x}}</ref> It is a neighborhood similar to the red light district, they both have strong ties to each other. In 1948, there was a gay Shinjuku tea shop and then by 1950s, gay bars started to open in Ni-ch\u014dme; the first gay bar was called Yanagi.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queer Japanese: Gender and Sexual identities through Linguistics Practices|last=Abe|first=Hideko|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2010|isbn=|location=New York|pages=165}}</ref>\n\n===Gay Bars (1960\u20131980)===\n\nThen by the 1960s, the number of gay bars started to expand in Tokyo, Japan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nakamura, Yanagihara, and Shida|first=Haruko, Yoshie, and Tetsuyuki|date=2017|title=Current Situation and Challenges of Building a Japanese LGBTQ Ephemera Collection at Yale|url=https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2700&context=jeal|journal=Journal of East Asian Libraries|volume=165|pages=1\u201318|via=}}</ref> In the 1960s, it went from fifty to six gay bars and it continued to increase over time.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia and Hall|first=Anna and Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=103}}</ref> By 1973, Tokyo opened a Onabe bar in Roppongi which is a district in Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia & Hall|first=Anna & Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=103}}</ref> The name of the bar was called Kik\u014dshi.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia and Hall|first=Anna and Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=103}}</ref>\n\n===StoneWall Japan (1988\u20132011)===\n\nIn 1988, participants from a program called JET created an organization and named it 'ATAGO' which they named after the room that they held the first meeting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=StoneWall Hapan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It stood for 'A Terribly Apropos Gay Organization.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was gay organization but then they wanted it to be more inclusive, so they added an 'L' for lesbians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The name then changed to 'ATAGLO'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This organization helped LGBT and JET participants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ATAGLO started out by producing newsletters, directory, phone counseling, and mentoring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the participants of LGBT and JET who identified themselves by 'Gayjet' expressed their concern with CLAIR, an organization that helps people of the LGBT+ community find employment and support JET participants, for censoring and discriminating those with LGBT+ voices within the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This group merged with ATAGLO and started to work on a proposal so that hey could become Special Interest Group (SIG) of the AJET organization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The purpose of this group was to be in publications, become more aware in the media, building relationships with LGBT+ and JET members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Then Gayjet created a proposal which collected 450 signatures of people that supported them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, CLAIR stated they would stop funding AJET if the word 'gay' was in the publication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Due to this, the group renamed the organization 'Stonewall' in March/April 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLater in 2014, the organization wanted to change the name to 'Life as a Gay JET' then to 'Life as a GLBT JET' then to 'Life as an LGBT Jet in Japan'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, AJET and Stonewall became distant from each other and their relationship dwindled down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, an AJET rep contacted a Stonewall member to see if they wanted to help rebuild AJET's LGBT social group for them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> So, in May 2011, 10 people that participated from JET helped to create new leadership roles and rebrand 'Stonewall Ajet'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They continued to have meetings to make changes to the organization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Because of the rise in participants, Stonewall AJET became an organization due to the amount of help they received.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Since establishing this new organization, they since they created a President, Vice President, Web Coordinator, Event Coordinator, and Block Leaders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Pride Parade (1994)===\n\nIn 1994, Japan had its first pride parade for gays and lesbians and it opened its first gay community center called ATKA.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref> This was a huge milestone for Japan's LGBT community.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBTFamily Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n===Gay Bars and Clubs (2010\u20132013)===\n\nIn 2010, there was a decline of gay clubs and bars in the area which decreased by one-third.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref> The decrease was due to the construction near Tokyo Metro Fukutoshin Line. The construction caused property values to increase in the area and also the internet. Then in August 17, 2012, it was banned to dance in clubs in Ni-ch\u014dme which is a popular district in Tokyo for the LGBT community.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n===Weddings (2012)===\n\nIn 2012, Japan announced that they would hold same-sex weddings at the Tokyo Disney Resort in Urayasu, Chiba.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/05/world/asia/social-media-embrace-same-sex-wedding-at-tokyo-disneyland.html|title=Gay Wedding Is Embraced by Disney in Tokyo|last=Tabuchi|first=Hiroko|date=2013|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Same-sex marriage was not legal in Japan until 2013 when Japanese citizens were legally allowed to marry their partner.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Same-Sex Marriage in Japan|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=12|issue=2|pages=160\u2013187|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2015.1016252|year=2016}}</ref> The first LGBT couple that got married at the Tokyo Disney resort were a lesbian couple.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Same-Sex Marriage in Japan|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=12|issue=2|pages=160\u2013187|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2015.1016252|year=2016|last1=Tamagawa|first1=Masami}}</ref> The couple, Koyuki Higashi and Hiroko Masuhara, got married on March 3, 2013 where they were legally allowed to get married.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Maree |first1=Claire |title=Weddings and white dresses: Media and sexual citizenship in Japan |journal=Sexualities |date=August 2016 |volume=20 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=212\u2013233 |doi=10.1177/1363460716645790|hdl=11343/220615 }}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nMajority of the public spaces for the LGBT community are in Shinjuku Ni-Ch\u014dme. Starting from 2010, there was a count of 300 gay bars located in this LGBT friendly community.<ref name=Baudinette/>\n\nIn Tokyo, there are other gay areas that have gay bars and are exposed to LGBT culture. Areas such as Ueno, Asakusa, Shimbashi, and Ikebukuro have gay bars, however, not more than Ni-ch\u014dme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/tokyo/bars-nightlife|title=Bars|last=|first=|date=|website=Time Out|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTokyo offers a range variety of cultural entertainment within the LGBT sports team, cultural and religious groups in its community.\n\n'''List of Gay Bars in 2013'''\n\nIn Shinjuku, there was a total of 297 gay bars\u2014in Shinjuku ni-ch\u014dme 291, Kabukicho 4, and Nishi-Shinjuku 2. In Ueno 95, Asakusa 67, Shinbashi 66, Ikebukuro 21, Shibuya 8, and Nakano 6. This is a list of all the gay bars in 2013, lesbian bars were not included in this list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/tokyo/bars-nightlife|title=Bars in Tokyo|last=|first=|date=|website=Time Out|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Institutions ==\nIn Tokyo, Japan, there is a lesbian group by the name of Regumi.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia & Hall|first=Anna & Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=104}}</ref> The word Regumi is another word for lesbian in Japan.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia & Hall|first=Anna & Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=105}}</ref> The short version for regumi is rezi which is an insulting term in Japanese.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia & Hall|first=Anna & Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=105}}</ref>\n\nThere is a Gay and Lesbian Deaf Rainbow Alliance or the Tokyo Lesbian and Gay Deaf Community (TLGDC) which is located in Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nakamura|first=Karen|date=|title=Trans/Disability: Disability, Queer Sexualities, and Transsexuality from a Comparative Ethnographic Perspective|url=http://www.p.u-tokyo.ac.jp/cbfe/activity/doc/05_doc1_20120119.pdf|journal=Journal of Trans and Disability|volume=|pages=1\u201318|via=}}</ref> One of the group members, Taski Tade, conducted an interview that was later translated to English.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Gay Games|last=Symons|first=Caroline|publisher=Taylor & Francis Group|year=2010|isbn=|location=New York|pages=1\u201312}}</ref>\n\n== Recreation ==\nIn Tokyo, there are two pride parades: Tokyo Rainbow Pride and Tokyo Pride.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Itakura|first=Kyohei|date=|title=Making Japan\"Out-and-Proud\" Through Not-Yet Consensual Translation: A Case Study of Tokyo Rainbow Pride's Website|url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt6887040t/qt6887040t.pdf?t=o98c33|journal=Queer Cats Journal of LGBTQ Studies|volume=1|pages=1\u201331|via=}}</ref>\n\nBeginning of 1994, the International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association started to organize the pride parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2012/04/24/issues/tokyo-gets-double-dose-of-gay-pride-for-2012/#.XegnxJNKgWp|title=Tokyo gets double dose of gay pride for 2012|last=Siguenza|date=2012|website=Japan Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The first name was the Tokyo Lesbian and Gay Parade which was Japans first pride parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2012/04/24/issues/tokyo-gets-double-dose-of-gay-pride-for-2012/#.XegnxJNKgWp|title=Tokyo gets double dose of gay pride for 2012|last=Siguenza|date=2012|website=Japan Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Then in 2007, the name changed to Tokyo Pride parade. The parades took a break from 2008 to 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2012/04/24/issues/tokyo-gets-double-dose-of-gay-pride-for-2012/#.XegnxJNKgWp|title=Tokyo gets double dose of gay pride for 2012|last=Siguenza|date=2012|website=Japan Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2010, a write from Reuters stated that only 12.8 million showed up for the parade which is a small crowd of people compared to the typically Asian crows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-gay/japans-gay-community-parades-for-first-time-in-3-years-idUSTRE67D0NH20100814|title=Japan's gay community parades for first time in 3 years|last=Slodkowski|first=Antoni|date=2010|website=Reuters|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThen in May 2011, the Tokyo Rainbow Pride was born. The organizers in this group made sure that the pride parade would be held in Tokyo. They did this in case the other event called Tokyo Pride would not happen. The Prime Minister of Japan, Akie, Abe, attended the event in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/world/2014/04/27/japans-first-lady-shines-tokyo-pride|title=Japan's First Lady Shines At Tokyo Pride|last=Garcia|first=Michelle|date=2014|website=Advocate|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Tokyo Rainbow Pride 2017 ==\n\nThere is a week in Tokyo from April 29 to May 7 where it is rainbow week. In 2017, the pride parade was on May 7.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Itakura|first=Kyohei|date=|title=Making Japan \"Out-and-Proud\" Through Not-Yet-Consensual Translation: A Case Study of Tokyo Rainbow Pride's Website|url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt6887040t/qt6887040t.pdf?t=o98c33|journal=Queer Cats Journal of LGBTQ Studies|volume=1|pages=1\u201331|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\nMany male artists have been coming out of the closet and speaking publicly about being gay on talk shows and other t.v programs in Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.ph/20100915195608/http://www.allbusiness.com/services/motion-pictures/4939796-1.html|title=On Japanese TV, The Lady Is A Man Cross-dressing 'onnagata' Are Popular For Being Outspoken|last=Ryall|first=Julian|date=2010-09-15|website=All Business|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> With being famous, there comes a lot of talk on sexuality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.ph/20100915195608/http://www.allbusiness.com/services/motion-pictures/4939796-1.html#selection-1865.0-1865.91|title=On Japanese TV, The Lady Is A Man Cross-dressing 'onnagata' Are Popular For Being Outspoken|last=Ryall|first=Julia|date=2010-09-15|website=All Business|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> There are two pop culture critics that are an example of being gay and coming out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.ph/20100915195608/http://www.allbusiness.com/services/motion-pictures/4939796-1.html#selection-1865.0-1865.91|title=On Japanese TV, The Lady Is A Man Cross-dressing 'onnagata' Are Popular For Being Outspoken|last=Ryall|first=Julian|date=2010-09-15|website=All Business|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThere are some celebrities that will use being LGBT to get more attention from the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/being-hard-gay-for-laughs-and-cash-5806679|title=Being Hard Gay for Laughs and Cash|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|date=|website=Kotaku|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> One comedian, Masaki Sumitani, rose to fame by wearing leather promiscuous clothing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/being-hard-gay-for-laughs-and-cash-5806679|title=Being Hard Gay for Laughs and Cash|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|date=|website=Kotaku|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He wore a leather harness, cap, and boots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/being-hard-gay-for-laughs-and-cash-5806679|title=Being Hard Gay for Laughs and Cash|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|date=|website=Kotaku|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> By him thrusting while wearing this leather outfit had his fans scream for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/being-hard-gay-for-laughs-and-cash-5806679|title=Being Hard Hay for Laughs and Cash|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|date=|website=Kotaku|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, there were twelve women that were one of the first people to come out and label themselves as lesbians. They were publish in a magazine called Subarashi Onna.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/amp/en_us/article/pajx3m/lesbian-history-archive-artifacts|title=The First Lesbian Porn and 10 Other Revealing Artifacts from Lesbian History|last=Leckert|first=Oriana|date=2019|website=Vice|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThere are two transgender celebrities: Ai Haruna and Ayana Tsubaki, who are Japanese celebrities that became well known from popular TV shows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://japantoday.com/category/features/kuchikomi/television-perpetuates-outmoded-gender-stereotypes|title=Television perpetuates outmoded gender stereotypes|last=Kuchikomi|date=2009|website=Japan Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2011, a fashion model by the name of Hiromi came out as a lesbian to the public.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Transforming Japan: How Feminism and Diversity are Making a Difference|last=Fujimura-Fanselow|first=Kumiko|publisher=The Feminist Press|year=2011|isbn=|location=New York|pages=147\u2013196}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:LGBT culture in Tokyo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Merge to|LGBT culture in Tokyo|date=December 2019}}\n\nTokyo, Japan has the largest LGBT community all throughout Asia. Within the Japanese culture, it is very difficult for Japanese people to come out of the closet;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|date=2015|title=Same-Sex Marriage in Japan|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=12|issue=2|pages=160\u2013187|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2015.1016252}}</ref> the LGBT community faces homophobia amongst its own people.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Same-Sex Marriage in Japan|journal= Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=12|issue=2|pages=160\u2013187|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2015.1016252|year=2016}}</ref> In an online survey, there were only 5% of Japanese people that they knew someone who was Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, or Transgender which is reported to being second lowest out of the sixteen countries involved.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref>\n\nThere is a community in Japan called stone wall that aims to serve the LGBT community by providing them with an open and safe space that supports and celebrate their sexuality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+|last=|first=|date=|website=Stone Wall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This organization provides educational awareness, useful information, communicative online platforms, and fellowship opportunities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n===American Occupation of Japan (1945\u20131952)===\n\nBetween 1945\u20131952, the gay neighborhood of Ni-ch\u014dme<ref name=Baudinette>{{Cite journal|last=Baudinette|first=Thomas|date=2017|title=The spatialisation of desire in a Japanese gay district through signage|url=https://www.acme-journal.org/index.php/acme/article/view/1357|journal=ACME: An International Journal for Critical Geographies|volume=16|pages=501|via=}}</ref> came into existence which was around the time of the America Occupation of Japan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Luther & Boyd|first=Catherine & Douglas|date=1997|title=American Occupation Control Over Broadcasting in Japan|journal=Journal of Communication|volume=47|pages=39\u201359|doi=10.1111/j.1460-2466.1997.tb02705.x}}</ref> It is a neighborhood similar to the red light district, they both have strong ties to each other. In 1948, there was a gay Shinjuku tea shop and then by 1950s, gay bars started to open in Ni-ch\u014dme; the first gay bar was called Yanagi.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queer Japanese: Gender and Sexual identities through Linguistics Practices|last=Abe|first=Hideko|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2010|isbn=|location=New York|pages=165}}</ref>\n\n===Gay Bars (1960\u20131980)===\n\nThen by the 1960s, the number of gay bars started to expand in Tokyo, Japan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nakamura, Yanagihara, and Shida|first=Haruko, Yoshie, and Tetsuyuki|date=2017|title=Current Situation and Challenges of Building a Japanese LGBTQ Ephemera Collection at Yale|url=https://scholarsarchive.byu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2700&context=jeal|journal=Journal of East Asian Libraries|volume=165|pages=1\u201318|via=}}</ref> In the 1960s, it went from fifty to six gay bars and it continued to increase over time.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia and Hall|first=Anna and Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=103}}</ref> By 1973, Tokyo opened a Onabe bar in Roppongi which is a district in Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia & Hall|first=Anna & Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=103}}</ref> The name of the bar was called Kik\u014dshi.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia and Hall|first=Anna and Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=103}}</ref>\n\n===StoneWall Japan (1988\u20132011)===\n\nIn 1988, participants from a program called JET created an organization and named it 'ATAGO' which they named after the room that they held the first meeting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=StoneWall Hapan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It stood for 'A Terribly Apropos Gay Organization.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was gay organization but then they wanted it to be more inclusive, so they added an 'L' for lesbians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The name then changed to 'ATAGLO'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This organization helped LGBT and JET participants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ATAGLO started out by producing newsletters, directory, phone counseling, and mentoring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the participants of LGBT and JET who identified themselves by 'Gayjet' expressed their concern with CLAIR, an organization that helps people of the LGBT+ community find employment and support JET participants, for censoring and discriminating those with LGBT+ voices within the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This group merged with ATAGLO and started to work on a proposal so that hey could become Special Interest Group (SIG) of the AJET organization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The purpose of this group was to be in publications, become more aware in the media, building relationships with LGBT+ and JET members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Then Gayjet created a proposal which collected 450 signatures of people that supported them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, CLAIR stated they would stop funding AJET if the word 'gay' was in the publication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Due to this, the group renamed the organization 'Stonewall' in March/April 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nLater in 2014, the organization wanted to change the name to 'Life as a Gay JET' then to 'Life as a GLBT JET' then to 'Life as an LGBT Jet in Japan'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, AJET and Stonewall became distant from each other and their relationship dwindled down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However, an AJET rep contacted a Stonewall member to see if they wanted to help rebuild AJET's LGBT social group for them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> So, in May 2011, 10 people that participated from JET helped to create new leadership roles and rebrand 'Stonewall Ajet'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They continued to have meetings to make changes to the organization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Because of the rise in participants, Stonewall AJET became an organization due to the amount of help they received.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Since establishing this new organization, they since they created a President, Vice President, Web Coordinator, Event Coordinator, and Block Leaders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stonewalljapan.org/|title=Connecting Japan's LGBTQIA+ International Community|last=|first=|date=|website=Stonewall Japan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Pride Parade (1994)===\n\nIn 1994, Japan had its first pride parade for gays and lesbians and it opened its first gay community center called ATKA.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref> This was a huge milestone for Japan's LGBT community.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBTFamily Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n===Gay Bars and Clubs (2010\u20132013)===\n\nIn 2010, there was a decline of gay clubs and bars in the area which decreased by one-third.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref> The decrease was due to the construction near Tokyo Metro Fukutoshin Line. The construction caused property values to increase in the area and also the internet. Then in August 17, 2012, it was banned to dance in clubs in Ni-ch\u014dme which is a popular district in Tokyo for the LGBT community.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Coming Out of the Closet in Japan: An Exploratory Sociological Study|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=14|issue=5|pages=488\u2013518|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2017.1338172|year=2018}}</ref>\n\n===Weddings (2012)===\n\nIn 2012, Japan announced that they would hold same-sex weddings at the Tokyo Disney Resort in Urayasu, Chiba.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/05/world/asia/social-media-embrace-same-sex-wedding-at-tokyo-disneyland.html|title=Gay Wedding Is Embraced by Disney in Tokyo|last=Tabuchi|first=Hiroko|date=2013|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Same-sex marriage was not legal in Japan until 2013 where Japanese citizens were legally allowed to get married to their partner.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tamagawa|first=Masami|title=Same-Sex Marriage in Japan|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=12|issue=2|pages=160\u2013187|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2015.1016252|year=2016}}</ref> The first LGBT couple that got married at the Tokyo Disney resort were a lesbian couple.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Same-Sex Marriage in Japan|journal=Journal of GLBT Family Studies|volume=12|issue=2|pages=160\u2013187|doi=10.1080/1550428X.2015.1016252|year=2016|last1=Tamagawa|first1=Masami}}</ref> The couple, Koyuki Higashi and Hiroko Masuhara, got married on March 3, 2013 where they were legally allowed to get married.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Maree |first1=Claire |title=Weddings and white dresses: Media and sexual citizenship in Japan |journal=Sexualities |date=August 2016 |volume=20 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=212\u2013233 |doi=10.1177/1363460716645790|hdl=11343/220615 }}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nMajority of the public spaces for the LGBT community are in Shinjuku Ni-Ch\u014dme. Starting from 2010, there was a count of 300 gay bars located in this LGBT friendly community.<ref name=Baudinette/>\n\nIn Tokyo, there are other gay areas that have gay bars and are exposed to LGBT culture. Areas such as Ueno, Asakusa, Shimbashi, and Ikebukuro have gay bars, however, not more than Ni-ch\u014dme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/tokyo/bars-nightlife|title=Bars|last=|first=|date=|website=Time Out|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTokyo offers a range variety of cultural entertainment within the LGBT sports team, cultural and religious groups in its community.\n\n'''List of Gay Bars in 2013'''\n\nIn Shinjuku, there was a total of 297 gay bars\u2014in Shinjuku ni-ch\u014dme 291, Kabukicho 4, and Nishi-Shinjuku 2. In Ueno 95, Asakusa 67, Shinbashi 66, Ikebukuro 21, Shibuya 8, and Nakano 6. This is a list of all the gay bars in 2013, lesbian bars were not included in this list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/tokyo/bars-nightlife|title=Bars in Tokyo|last=|first=|date=|website=Time Out|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Institutions ==\nIn Tokyo, Japan, there is a lesbian group by the name of Regumi.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia & Hall|first=Anna & Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=104}}</ref> The word Regumi is another word for lesbian in Japan.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia & Hall|first=Anna & Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=105}}</ref> The short version for regumi is rezi which is an insulting term in Japanese.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality|last=Livia & Hall|first=Anna & Kira|publisher=Oxford University|year=1997|isbn=|location=New York|pages=105}}</ref>\n\nThere is a Gay and Lesbian Deaf Rainbow Alliance or the Tokyo Lesbian and Gay Deaf Community (TLGDC) which is located in Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nakamura|first=Karen|date=|title=Trans/Disability: Disability, Queer Sexualities, and Transsexuality from a Comparative Ethnographic Perspective|url=http://www.p.u-tokyo.ac.jp/cbfe/activity/doc/05_doc1_20120119.pdf|journal=Journal of Trans and Disability|volume=|pages=1\u201318|via=}}</ref> One of the group members, Taski Tade, conducted an interview that was later translated to English.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Gay Games|last=Symons|first=Caroline|publisher=Taylor & Francis Group|year=2010|isbn=|location=New York|pages=1\u201312}}</ref>\n\n== Recreation ==\nIn Tokyo, there are two pride parades: Tokyo Rainbow Pride and Tokyo Pride.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Itakura|first=Kyohei|date=|title=Making Japan\"Out-and-Proud\" Through Not-Yet Consensual Translation: A Case Study of Tokyo Rainbow Pride's Website|url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt6887040t/qt6887040t.pdf?t=o98c33|journal=Queer Cats Journal of LGBTQ Studies|volume=1|pages=1\u201331|via=}}</ref>\n\nBeginning of 1994, the International Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Intersex Association started to organize the pride parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2012/04/24/issues/tokyo-gets-double-dose-of-gay-pride-for-2012/#.XegnxJNKgWp|title=Tokyo gets double dose of gay pride for 2012|last=Siguenza|date=2012|website=Japan Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The first name was the Tokyo Lesbian and Gay Parade which was Japans first pride parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2012/04/24/issues/tokyo-gets-double-dose-of-gay-pride-for-2012/#.XegnxJNKgWp|title=Tokyo gets double dose of gay pride for 2012|last=Siguenza|date=2012|website=Japan Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Then in 2007, the name changed to Tokyo Pride parade. The parades took a break from 2008 to 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2012/04/24/issues/tokyo-gets-double-dose-of-gay-pride-for-2012/#.XegnxJNKgWp|title=Tokyo gets double dose of gay pride for 2012|last=Siguenza|date=2012|website=Japan Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2010, a write from Reuters stated that only 12.8 million showed up for the parade which is a small crowd of people compared to the typically Asian crows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-gay/japans-gay-community-parades-for-first-time-in-3-years-idUSTRE67D0NH20100814|title=Japan's gay community parades for first time in 3 years|last=Slodkowski|first=Antoni|date=2010|website=Reuters|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThen in May 2011, the Tokyo Rainbow Pride was born. The organizers in this group made sure that the pride parade would be held in Tokyo. They did this in case the other event called Tokyo Pride would not happen. The Prime Minister of Japan, Akie, Abe, attended the event in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/world/2014/04/27/japans-first-lady-shines-tokyo-pride|title=Japan's First Lady Shines At Tokyo Pride|last=Garcia|first=Michelle|date=2014|website=Advocate|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Tokyo Rainbow Pride 2017 ==\n\nThere is a week in Tokyo from April 29 to May 7 where it is rainbow week. In 2017, the pride parade was on May 7.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Itakura|first=Kyohei|date=|title=Making Japan \"Out-and-Proud\" Through Not-Yet-Consensual Translation: A Case Study of Tokyo Rainbow Pride's Website|url=https://escholarship.org/content/qt6887040t/qt6887040t.pdf?t=o98c33|journal=Queer Cats Journal of LGBTQ Studies|volume=1|pages=1\u201331|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\nMany male artists have been coming out of the closet and speaking publicly about being gay on talk shows and other t.v programs in Tokyo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.ph/20100915195608/http://www.allbusiness.com/services/motion-pictures/4939796-1.html|title=On Japanese TV, The Lady Is A Man Cross-dressing 'onnagata' Are Popular For Being Outspoken|last=Ryall|first=Julian|date=2010-09-15|website=All Business|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> With being famous, there comes a lot of talk on sexuality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.ph/20100915195608/http://www.allbusiness.com/services/motion-pictures/4939796-1.html#selection-1865.0-1865.91|title=On Japanese TV, The Lady Is A Man Cross-dressing 'onnagata' Are Popular For Being Outspoken|last=Ryall|first=Julia|date=2010-09-15|website=All Business|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> There are two pop culture critics that are an example of being gay and coming out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.ph/20100915195608/http://www.allbusiness.com/services/motion-pictures/4939796-1.html#selection-1865.0-1865.91|title=On Japanese TV, The Lady Is A Man Cross-dressing 'onnagata' Are Popular For Being Outspoken|last=Ryall|first=Julian|date=2010-09-15|website=All Business|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThere are some celebrities that will use being LGBT to get more attention from the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/being-hard-gay-for-laughs-and-cash-5806679|title=Being Hard Gay for Laughs and Cash|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|date=|website=Kotaku|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> One comedian, Masaki Sumitani, rose to fame by wearing leather promiscuous clothing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/being-hard-gay-for-laughs-and-cash-5806679|title=Being Hard Gay for Laughs and Cash|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|date=|website=Kotaku|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He wore a leather harness, cap, and boots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/being-hard-gay-for-laughs-and-cash-5806679|title=Being Hard Gay for Laughs and Cash|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|date=|website=Kotaku|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> By him thrusting while wearing this leather outfit had his fans scream for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/being-hard-gay-for-laughs-and-cash-5806679|title=Being Hard Hay for Laughs and Cash|last=Ashcraft|first=Brian|date=|website=Kotaku|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, there were twelve women that were one of the first people to come out and label themselves as lesbians. They were publish in a magazine called Subarashi Onna.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/amp/en_us/article/pajx3m/lesbian-history-archive-artifacts|title=The First Lesbian Porn and 10 Other Revealing Artifacts from Lesbian History|last=Leckert|first=Oriana|date=2019|website=Vice|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThere are two transgender celebrities: Ai Haruna and Ayana Tsubaki, who are Japanese celebrities that became well known from popular TV shows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://japantoday.com/category/features/kuchikomi/television-perpetuates-outmoded-gender-stereotypes|title=Television perpetuates outmoded gender stereotypes|last=Kuchikomi|date=2009|website=Japan Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2011, a fashion model by the name of Hiromi came out as a lesbian to the public.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Transforming Japan: How Feminism and Diversity are Making a Difference|last=Fujimura-Fanselow|first=Kumiko|publisher=The Feminist Press|year=2011|isbn=|location=New York|pages=147\u2013196}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:LGBT culture in Tokyo]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LGBT_Culture_in_Tokyo"}
